This is a truly great app. With both time lapse and stop motion capabilities, it is quite versatile. It's editing capabilities are amongst the best I've seen, with full control over frame rate, video output size with a modest choice of codecs. You can also add a few special effects, music/audio and rotate the frames individual frames. What this app lacks, is control over the exposure. There are lesser apps with exposure compensation  control that allow you brighten or darken the image. The lack of this feature limits it's use in some instances, such as a time lapse capture of cloud or towards the morning/afternoon sun, where exposure compensation is very handy. This app would benefit greatly from at least this feature. Would be far better with more detailed exposure controls. Overall, it's a great app packed with good features. I have no trouble recommend this app!

Nice app, but has a few issues.   It crashes on Android phones.  I've used it on three different ones, and it has crashed on all 3.  It runs well on iOS, however well - iOS sucks in general.   The LapseIt folks have apparently ceased creating LapseIt for iOS, since the only version available there is the older 2.4.  I suspect the reason it's crashing on my Android phones is because I changed it to write to SD card; perhaps it can't write at some point during a capture (even though there's plenty of space), and crashes randomly (sometimes after 30 minutes, an hour, two hours - it's random).  So I tried switching back to have it write to internal storage - but there's no option for this.   In the Settings entry for Output Folder - it only has the option "USE SD-CARD".    If I select "I UNDERSTAND" in order to browse folders to store it in - there's now way to revert back to the still-empty Internal Storage location.  It's a great app, and if not for these issues I'd give it 5 stars.   But alas - two stars until these problems get fixed.

content: Initial use of the app works great, then when you go to run a full day it stops working. I emails support and got no response.  2 features needed urgently  - 1 the scheduled needs to be stored in such a way that it is not lost if you hit the stop button instead of the Pause,. If the app is shut down or the phone looses power and is restarted. - 2 An option that when turned on Does everything it can to keep the app running - If it stops working it auto restarts and checks the schedule.
replyContent:
Probably you did something wrong either as using the app in background mode or turned off the screen when capturing. Or you misused the settings of the app ( For example you could have set it to take one picture every 3 hours and not every 3 minutes.

Don't rate the app badly because you cannot use it correctly ( Even if is really simple ).
Regards

content: When I add good quality MP3s (320kbps) from my library they sound horrible on my rendered video. Don't think I'll use the app much because of this.  Typical no response from the developer on how to fix it.  Disappointed. Rendered vids don't play on standard video player requiring download of 3rd party player like VLC Player. Awesome render doesn't work on Samsung Note 2. NOT IMPRESSED THAT DEV DOESN'T RESPOND TO FEEDBACK AFTER PAYING FOR APP!
replyContent: The awesome render engine mode creates H264 full compatible video files, if you cannot use it will still create compatible video files but a few mp3 files will not work well due being created with older mp3 codecs. You can either encode your mp3 sound to a new version, use another song or update your Android version to use the "awesome render" mode

content: Easy to create professional looking time lapse sequences. The only limiting factor is your imagination and battery capacity. TIPS; try to match total frames to length of capture. IE; you want to capture a one hour sequence and watch it over 30 seconds you might try 10 second intervals. Experimenting is slow but fun. You'll be surprised at the results.  Use a BT headset in order to get phone calls. Keep phone on charger if possible. It will use a lot of battery. Airplane mode is good if not expecting calls.

So, fine, it's not a big deal to turn on compatibility mode.  Except...  With compatibility mode turned on, if you're doing stop-motion capture, the onionskin image shows up at a right angle to your camera's current orientation.  You end up with two images at right angles to each other superimposed on your screen.  This makes the onionskinning, which should be quite helpful, worse than useless.  It is actually *more* confusing to have the right-angle onionskin than to have nothing at all.  That said, It's fun and easy to make videos with the app, and I've enjoyed using it so far.    My one feature request would be a way to delete individual frames. Sometimes a hand or something gets in your shot by accident, and it would be great to be able to remove that kind of mistake from your final video.

As a photographer i wanted a simple way to do time lapse. And this app is the answer! I use it nearly every day shooting anything from flowers blooming to a cruise through the country. Would have given it 5 stars and more if it allowed for HDR imaging.

I would love to add: - The ability to ignore incoming calls when making a time lapse Currently I put the phone in airplane mode because incoming calls do not merely pause the capture, they stop it completely and it cannot be restarted. - The ability for the app to continue running in the background It's frustrating that the app doesn't have the ability to continue running in the background.  I have to choose between using my phone as a time lapse camera only, or using it for everything else.  Enable the photo capturing in the background would be great for longer captures such as road trips, where the other functionality still comes in handy (GPS mapping, text messages, phone calls). - The ability to merge two capture projects together into one Because of point number one (phone calls stop the capture rather than pausing it), I would love to simply start a new capture with the same settings and then merge them together after the fact. - Delete single images from the capture Currently I can trim the start/end points but I can't delete single frames if I so choose.
It does what I want it to.

This app is exactly what I was looking for; it's well designed, is highly configurable and renders to superb quality MP4 at 720p or lower resolutions. You have the choice to do multiple renders at different frame rates in the app itself after all the images have been captured, and the app stores all the frames, so if you want to render the stills into a movie on your computer, you can. Most impressive. Just be aware that you'll need a decent amount of internal storage if you want to store thousands of frames at 720p. Reckon on 650Kb for each 720p frame. Put another way, five minutes' worth of 720p frames at 30fps will cost you about  5.8Gb of storage, and that's before you get to do the render. Still, this is an awesome app. Give your lens a clean before you start.
